Let the polar angle $\theta$ and the ordinate of the point $(x,\,y)$ of
the plane be to a parametre $t$, e.g. such that $\theta = t$, $y = kt$.
The above diagram shows that $\displaystyle\frac{x}{kt} = \cot{t}$. Into
this we can substitute $\displaystyle t = \frac{y}{k}$, whence we get an
equation $$\begin{aligned}
x \;=\; y\cot\frac{y}{k}\end{aligned}$$ between $x$ and $y$. The given
proportionalities as locus condition, the point $(x,\,y)$ draws a plane
curve called [*quadratrix*]{}. If we change the $x$ and $y$ coordinates,
the equation of the quadratrix is $$\begin{aligned}
y \;=\; x\cot\frac{x}{k}.\end{aligned}$$ The equation (2) defines an
even function $x \mapsto y$, where for $x$ is allowed all real values at
which the right hand side of (2) is defined, thus $x \neq n\pi k$
($n \in \mathbb{Z}$).

